.86, "target_achievement": 1.0, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "This is the best-supported route to the target as written because it relies on direct extraterrestrial glucose delivery, now supported by Bennu sample analysis, followed by borate-assisted stabilization/phosphorylation, which also aligns with recent literature on regioselective glucose phosphorylation in evaporative settings. It is not a de novo terrestrial synthesis route, but it does achieve the target credibly and coherently under the multi-source model emphasized by the research.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Distinguish this pathway clearly as delivery plus preservation rather than endogenous synthesis", "Add concentration and survival assumptions for meteoritic glucose in surface pools", "Consider coupling this pathway to downstream biochemical utilization rather than treating phosphorylation only as a side module"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.78, "rxn_003": 0.92, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.95, "rxn_007": 0.74}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.86, "pathway_coherence": 0.81, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.78, "overall_confidence": 0.84, "feedback": "This pathway is mostly strong because it retains the robust HCN-to-C3 sugar chemistry and goethite-mediated C6 formation. The formamide branch, however, is not actually necessary for glucose production as presented and reads more as feedstock convergence than a mechanistically integral glucose route. The pathway remains plausible overall but somewhat overstates the role of formamide in reaching the target.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_007"], "suggestions": ["Clarify whether formamide participates directly in sugar chemistry or is only a parallel nitrogen chemistry module", "Keep the HCN-to-glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde step as the actual productive branch", "Strengthen the final glucose-forming isomerization with explicit conditions"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P9", "overall_confidence": 0.83, "network_feedback": "The network is topologically strong and substantially better than a naive formose-only glucose network. It contains adequate molecule and reaction counts, multiple hubs, multiple convergence points, and clear environmental interconnection from hydrothermal feedstocks and surface photochemistry into later sugar assembly and stabilization. Its overall strategy aligns well with the literature conclusion that glucose should be treated as a convergent product of multiple modules rather than a single selective route. The strongest parts are the cyanosulfidic production of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde, the goethite-catalyzed C3+C3 condensation to ketohexoses, borate-assisted glucose stabilization/phosphorylation, and inclusion of extraterrestrial delivery. These are all well supported by the research findings.\n\nThe main weaknesses are chemical specificity and literature fidelity in several weaker branches. The hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde module is too optimistic as written. The formaldehyde-driven formose modules are correctly described as weak, but still somewhat overused given the 2025 evidence that mild formose conditions preferentially generate branched sugars rather than linear glucose precursors. Pentose-plus-formaldehyde extension to hexoses and the generic ketohexose-to-glucose step are underdefined and less experimentally anchored than the rest of the network. The glyoxylate branch also omits the major unresolved problem of DHF supply. Another issue is schema-level completeness relative to the requested network standard: the summarized network does not show reaction-specific mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface step, nor reaction-level literature citations in the reasoning fields, so full literature-alignment compliance is incomplete.\n\nOverall, this is a good but not approval-level network under the strict >=0.9 criterion. It is conceptually modern, convergent, and literature-aware, but several routes remain partly speculative and some required supporting detail is missing.", "hub_quality": 0.91, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 67541.12720489502, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T14:33:14.602302", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glucose\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Glucose. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of glucose: routes, evidence, and unresolved challenges\n\n**No single demonstrated pathway selectively produces glucose from simple prebiotic molecules \u2014 making it one of the hardest unsolved problems in origin-of-life chemistry.** The formose reaction, the classical route from formaldehyde to sugars discovered in 1861, generates over 50 products with glucose comprising a small and variable fraction, and a landmark 2025 NMR study revealed it fundamentally produces branched rather than linear sugars. Alternative routes \u2014 cyanosulfidic photochemistry, the glyoxylate scenario, mineral-guided cycles, and extraterrestrial delivery \u2014 each solve part of the problem but none yet achieve selective glucose synthesis under plausible prebiotic conditions. The first detection of glucose in pristine asteroid Bennu samples (Furukawa et al., *Nature Geoscience*, 2025) confirms that hexoses existed in the early solar system, but the mechanism of their formation remains debated. This report synthesizes the current state of knowledge across all proposed pathways, intermediates, environmental settings, catalysts, and experimental evidence to guide synthesis network design.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The formose reaction remains the canonical but deeply flawed pathway\n\nThe formose reaction, discovered by Aleksandr Butlerov in 1861 (*Comptes rendus de l'Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences*, 53:145\u2013147), converts formaldehyde into a mixture of sugars under alkaline conditions. Ronald Breslow elucidated the autocatalytic mechanism in 1959 (*Tetrahedron Letters*, 1(21):22\u201326), proposing a cycle in which glycolaldehyde \u2014 the simplest sugar \u2014 catalyzes its own production from formaldehyde through a sequence of aldol additions, aldose-ketose isomerizations, and retroaldol fragmentations. The cycle proceeds: formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde (C2) \u2192 glyceraldehyde (C3) \u2192 dihydroxyacetone (C3) \u2192 tetrulose (C4) \u2192 aldotetrose (C4) \u2192 two molecules of glycolaldehyde, with branching pathways producing C5 and C6 sugars at each stage. Appayee and Breslow updated the mechanism in 2014 (*JACS*, 136:3720\u20133723), showing via deuterium labeling that the isomerization steps proceed through a **hydride shift** rather than the originally proposed enediolate intermediate.\n\nThe reaction exhibits three kinetic phases described by Tran, Yi, and Fahrenbach (*Chemical Science*, 2023, 14:9589\u20139599): a lag phase during which only Cannizzaro disproportionation occurs, an exponential phase once glycolaldehyde exceeds a critical concentration (**\u22653 ppm** per Socha, Weiss, and Sakharov, 1980), and a degradation phase in which sugars polymerize into intractable tars. Recent computational work (2025, *J. Chem. Phys.*, 163(8)) quantified the fundamental kinetic problem: the Cannizzaro disproportionation barrier is **16.5 kcal/mol**, lower than both formaldehyde dimerization (**26.9 kcal/mol**) and the productive formose cycle (**18.0 kcal/mol**), meaning the parasitic side reaction is always kinetically favored over sugar formation.\n\nTypical experimental conditions use **0.1\u20131.8 M formaldehyde** with Ca(OH)\u2082 catalyst at **50\u201380\u00b0C** and pH \u2265 12. Total sugar yields are dismal: Omran et al. (*Life*, 2020, 10:125) reported only **0.003%** of starting formaldehyde remained as sugars under hydrothermal conditions (120\u00b0C, pH 12.5, 1 hour), with the thermodynamic minimum being carboxylic acids rather than sugars. Nishijima et al. (*Angewandte Chemie Int. Ed.*, 2026) found that non-target product molecular formulas outnumber monosaccharide species by **4\u20137 fold** at all reaction stages. One notable finding from Omran et al. (2020) is that under NaOH-only catalysis (no divalent cation) at 80\u00b0C, glucose constitutes approximately **80 mol%** of detectable sugars \u2014 remarkable selectivity, though overall sugar yields remain below 1%.\n\nA critical 2025 finding fundamentally challenges the formose reaction's viability. Pulletikurti, Lin, Sutton, Liotta, and Krishnamurthy (*Chem*, April 2025) used NMR spectroscopy under mild conditions and demonstrated that the formose reaction produces **only branched sugars, not linear sugars like glucose or ribose**. They concluded that \"controlling the aldol reaction of formaldehyde to selectively produce linear aldoses appears unfeasible,\" calling for the community to \"search for alternative solutions.\"\n\n---\n\n## 2. Alternative synthesis routes each address different aspects of the problem\n\n### Cyanosulfidic photochemistry bypasses formaldehyde\n\nJohn Sutherland's group at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology developed a fundamentally different approach. Ritson and Sutherland (*Nature Chemistry*, 2012, 4:895\u2013899) demonstrated that glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde form directly from HCN through UV-driven Cu(I)\u2194Cu(II) photoredox cycling \u2014 a Kiliani-Fischer-type reductive homologation that bypasses the problematic formaldehyde dimerization entirely. The key 2015 paper by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (*Nature Chemistry*, 7:301\u2013307) showed that precursors for ribonucleotides, amino acids, and lipids all derive from **reductive homologation of HCN** using H\u2082S as reductant and UV light as energy source \u2014 a unified \"cyanosulfidic protometabolism.\"\n\nThe most recent advance is Ritson and Sutherland's 2023 work (*Nature Chemistry*, 15:1470\u20131477) showing that **thiophosphate (PSO\u2083\u00b3\u207b)** \u2014 formed from meteorite-derived phosphite oxidized by H\u2082S under UV \u2014 is a far more effective photoreductant than H\u2082S alone. Specific yields include glycolaldehyde at **~34%** (with phosphate buffer, pH 6.5) and glyceraldehyde at **~14%** overall after evaporation. Tetroses and pentoses are accessible through continued Kiliani-Fischer homologation **without progressing to higher sugars**, potentially solving the selectivity problem for smaller sugars. However, this pathway has not been extended to selective hexose or glucose production.\n\n### The glyoxylate scenario offers cleaner chemistry\n\nAlbert Eschenmoser proposed glyoxylate \u2014 a \"carboxylated formaldehyde\" \u2014 as an alternative C1 building block (*Tetrahedron*, 2007, 63:12821\u201312844). Experimental validation by Sagi, Krishnamurthy, and colleagues (*JACS*, 2012, 134:3577\u20133589) showed that dihydroxyfumarate (DHF, the formal glyoxylate dimer) reacts with glyceraldehyde to produce xylulose and ribulose in **~60% yield** \u2014 with near-quantitative conversion and clean, selective formation of ketoses with no detectable aldoses. This stands in stark contrast to the messy formose reaction. Krishnamurthy's group further developed the \"glyoxylose reaction\" framework (*Chem*, 2023), proposing repetitive aldol condensations with glyoxylate followed by carbonyl migrations and decarboxylations. The challenge remains that no known prebiotic pathway produces DHF itself in sufficient quantities, and selective glucose formation has not been demonstrated through this route.\n\n### Hydrothermal vent chemistry and extraterrestrial delivery\n\nAlkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type, 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide favorable conditions for formaldehyde production from CO\u2082 reduction by H\u2082 across Fe(Ni)S membranes, followed by formose-type sugar synthesis at mild alkaline conditions. Nick Lane's group at UCL demonstrated proof-of-principle CO\u2082 reduction to formaldehyde and subsequent ribose formation (~0.06%) in simulated vent reactors. Thermophoretic concentration in microporous vent structures can amplify organic molecule concentrations up to **5,000-fold**. However, sugar stability remains problematic at vent temperatures (see Section 5).\n\nExtraterrestrial delivery provides a complementary source. Furukawa et al. (*PNAS*, 2019, 116:24440\u201324445) first detected ribose, arabinose, xylose, and lyxose in the Murchison and NWA 801 meteorites at **2.3\u2013180 ppb**. Their landmark 2025 finding of **glucose in pristine Bennu asteroid samples** (*Nature Geoscience*, 19:19\u201324) confirmed that hexoses \u2014 including the primary biological energy source \u2014 existed in the early solar system. Glycolaldehyde, detected in interstellar space by Hollis, Lovas, and Jewell (*Astrophysical Journal Letters*, 2000) and in the solar-type protostar IRAS 16293-2422 by J\u00f8rgensen et al. (*Astrophysical Journal Letters*, 2012), could have survived cometary delivery to early Earth in quantities up to **10\u00b2\u00b3 kg**.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are the critical C1 and C2 entry points\n\n**Formaldehyde (HCHO)** is the foundational C1 building block for nearly all proposed prebiotic sugar pathways. Pinto, Gladstone, and Yung (*Science*, 1980, 210:183\u2013185) estimated atmospheric photochemical production rates of **~10\u00b9\u00b9 mol/year** on early Earth, yielding a steady-state oceanic concentration of approximately **10\u207b\u00b3 M** \u2014 likely an overestimate given Cannizzaro losses and other decomposition channels. Formaldehyde is abundant in the interstellar medium and cometary ices, thermally stable below 300\u00b0C, and hydrates to methanediol in aqueous solution. Weber (2002) argued it may be the only C1 CHO molecule capable of generating complex organics for life's origin.\n\n**Glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO)**, the simplest sugar, serves as the autocatalytic \"linchpin\" of the Breslow cycle. Its formation from formaldehyde is the critical bottleneck: the uncatalyzed dimerization barrier is **45.3 kcal/mol** (Kua et al., *J. Phys. Chem. A*, 2013, 117:12658), requiring \"umpolung\" of formaldehyde's electrophilic carbon. Once present, glycolaldehyde enables aldol addition with formaldehyde to produce glyceraldehyde (C3) through much lower barriers. Atmospheric glycolaldehyde production on early Earth was estimated at only ~10\u2077 mol/yr from direct photochemistry, with the formose reaction potentially contributing ~2 \u00d7 10\u2078 mol/yr.\n\n**Glyceraldehyde**, the simplest chiral sugar and first aldotriose, is the central branch point in the network. It isomerizes to **dihydroxyacetone (DHA)** via the Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein transformation, with equilibrium strongly favoring the ketose form under basic conditions. The C3 stage is where pathways diverge: C3 + C2 \u2192 pentoses (ribose for RNA); C3 + C3 \u2192 hexoses (including glucose for metabolism); C3 + C1 \u2192 tetroses. Hexose formation specifically proceeds through multiple routes \u2014 C3 + C3 aldol condensation (primarily yielding ketohexoses like fructose and sorbose), C4 + C2, and C5 + C1 \u2014 with interconversion between glucose, fructose, and mannose occurring through enediol intermediates.\n\n**Glucose is the most thermodynamically stable aldohexose** because \u03b2-D-glucopyranose adopts the \u2074C\u2081 chair conformation in which all hydroxyl groups and the CH\u2082OH substituent occupy equatorial positions \u2014 unique among the 16 aldohexose stereoisomers. Its open-chain aldehyde form constitutes only **~0.002\u20130.02%** of the equilibrium mixture, making it the least reactive hexose toward degradation. This thermodynamic and kinetic stability may explain glucose's biological selection, but the formose reaction primarily produces fructose (via C3 + C3 condensation), which must undergo Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein rearrangement to yield glucose and mannose.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Minerals serve as both catalysts and stabilizers across distinct environmental settings\n\n### Borate minerals are the most important stabilizing agents\n\nThe seminal work by Ricardo, Carrigan, Olcott, and Benner (*Science*, 2004, 303:196) demonstrated that borate ions form reversible complexes with 1,2-diol groups on sugars, locking them in their cyclic furanose forms and suppressing base-catalyzed enolization and degradation. Ribose, which decomposes within minutes under alkaline conditions, **remained stable for days** with borate at room temperature. Furukawa et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2013, 43:353\u2013361) showed borate **selectively stabilizes ribose** over other aldopentoses. Kim, Ricardo, and Benner (*JACS*, 2011, 133:9457\u20139468) demonstrated that combined **borate, molybdate, and calcium minerals** guide formation of tetroses, pentoses, and heptoses in \"hands-off\" experiments at 65\u00b0C. Molybdate catalyzes the B\u00edlik rearrangement converting branched pentoses to linear forms \u2014 essential for producing biologically relevant sugars.\n\nFor glucose specifically, Furukawa et al. (*Scientific Reports*, 2023) showed that borate-rich evaporative environments enable **regioselective phosphorylation** of glucose to glucose 6-phosphate and gluconate to 6-phosphogluconate using thermal evaporation \u2014 establishing a non-enzymatic proto-glycolysis and proto-pentose phosphate pathway. Borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite, kernite) are enriched in volcanic/hydrothermal settings, and their geological availability on Hadean Earth is supported by tourmaline deposits dating to **3,300\u20133,450 Ma** in the Barberton belt, South Africa.\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals catalyze carbon fixation and sugar-relevant reactions\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**, a structural analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters in ferredoxin enzymes, forms abiotically in alkaline hydrothermal chimneys at 40\u201380\u00b0C (maximum yield at **75\u00b0C**, Roldan et al., *Astrobiology*, 2015) and catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction. **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** is central to W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis and drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates. Most relevant for hexose synthesis, **iron(III) hydroxide oxide (goethite, Fe(OH)O)** efficiently catalyzes condensation of glyceraldehyde to ketohexoses at just 25\u00b0C and pH 5\u20136: Weber (*J. Mol. Evol.*, 1992, 35:1\u20136) reported yields of **sorbose (15.2%), fructose (12.9%), psicose (6.1%), and tagatose (5.6%)** with no hexose decomposition observed even after 96 days. This iron hydroxide pathway is notable for its mild conditions, reasonable yields, and product stability.\n\n### Environmental settings create distinct reaction zones\n\nThree primary settings have been proposed, each with different advantages:\n\n- **Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311): Moderate temperatures allow longer sugar survival; CaCO\u2083 chemical garden membranes create steep pH gradients with formose-active alkaline zones and cooler protective zones; thermophoretic concentration in micropores amplifies reactants; activity persists for >30,000 years. Sugar stability is limiting: Larralde, Robertson, and Miller (*PNAS*, 1995, 92:8158) measured ribose half-life at **73 minutes at 100\u00b0C** and **~44 years at 0\u00b0C** at pH 7. Glucose and other hexoses have comparable half-lives.\n\n- **Volcanic hot spring pools with wet-dry cycling**: Damer and Deamer (*Astrobiology*, 2020, 20:429\u2013452) proposed that fluctuating hot spring pools drive condensation during drying, encapsulation during rehydration, and provide access to borate and silicate minerals. The 3.48 Ga Dresser Formation in Western Australia confirms such environments existed on early Earth. Evaporation concentrates reactants and strengthens borate-sugar ester bonds, while rehydration releases substrates.\n\n- **Photochemically active surface environments**: Essential for cyanosulfidic chemistry (UV at **254 nm** principal emission; early Earth had orders-of-magnitude higher UV flux at 200\u2013300 nm due to absence of the ozone layer). ZnS (band gap ~3.6 eV, absorbing UV <345 nm) and TiO\u2082 serve as mineral semiconductor photocatalysts. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes RNA polymerization with rate constants **100\u20131,000\u00d7 greater** than hydrolysis rates (Ferris, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*, 2006, 361:1777\u20131786).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Experimental evidence spans meteorites, photochemistry, and mineral catalysis\n\nThe experimental landscape for prebiotic glucose synthesis spans several complementary approaches:\n\n**Formose reaction experiments** demonstrate the range of possible products. Omran et al. (2020) showed that CaCO\u2083-based chemical gardens (hydrothermal vent analogs) catalyze the formose reaction to produce glucose, ribose, and other monosaccharides, with glucose dominating (~80 mol% of sugars) under NaOH-only conditions. Lamour et al. (*Life*, 2019) demonstrated mechanochemical formose conditions (ball milling) producing hexoses as **66%** of the sugar mixture after 28 days, with **~95% selectivity** toward aldoses/ketoses versus ~50\u201360% in aqueous solution. Hashidzume (*RSC Advances*, 2023) achieved nearly 100% hexose + heptose yield using microwave-irradiated Ca(OH)\u2082 + formaldehyde at 150\u00b0C for 1 minute \u2014 though under conditions far from prebiotically plausible.\n\n**Mineral catalyst studies** provide some of the most promising results for hexose formation. Weber's 1992 iron hydroxide experiments remain among the best for selective hexose production, yielding ~28% combined ketohexoses from glyceraldehyde at 25\u00b0C with no decomposition over 96 days. Jong et al. (*Angewandte Chemie*, 2025) showed that different mineral environments (hydroxyapatite, goethite, montmorillonite, TiO\u2082) produce distinct formose product distributions, with environmental mineral history effectively \"transferred\" to sugar product profiles. The Camprubi, Harrison, and Jordan experiment (*Astrobiology*, 2022) demonstrated that acetyl phosphate stabilizes ribose **10-fold** in the formose reaction, though the mechanism was product stabilization rather than directed synthesis.\n\n**Electrochemical approaches** represent an emerging frontier. Cestellos-Blanco et al. (*Joule*, 2022, 6:2503\u20132521) converted CO\u2082 electrochemically to glycolaldehyde (on Cu nanoparticles) and formaldehyde (on boron-doped diamond electrodes, **~62% Faradaic efficiency**), with subsequent formose reaction producing C4\u2013C8 sugars including glucose. A 2025 *PNAS* study achieved **60\u201380% carbon conversion** for pentose/tetrose/triose mixtures and >20% for hexoses through combined electro-, photo-, and organo-catalysis.\n\n**Meteoritic evidence** provides ground truth for what abiotic chemistry actually produces. Furukawa et al.'s detection of ribose and other sugars in Murchison and NWA 801 meteorites (2019) at **2.3\u2013180 ppb**, confirmed by \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C extraterrestrial signatures, and the subsequent detection of glucose in Bennu samples (2025), demonstrate that formose-like chemistry operates in asteroid parent bodies. The absence of deoxyribose in all samples supports the RNA world hypothesis. Yi et al. (*JACS Au*, 2023) noted that C6 aldonates (stable sugar acid forms) are abundant in the Murchison meteorite while canonical sugars are absent, suggesting aldonates may serve as stable reservoirs that convert back to pentoses through decarboxylation.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The selectivity, stability, and chirality problems remain the central bottlenecks\n\n### The selectivity problem is more severe than previously recognized\n\nThe formose reaction was already known to produce **50+ different sugar species** (Shapiro, *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*, 1988). Orgel's influential 2004 review (*Critical Reviews in Biochemistry and Molecular Biology*, 39:99\u2013123) acknowledged that directed formose chemistry would be \"ideal\" but declared the evidence insufficient for prebiotic ribose availability. The 2025 Krishnamurthy NMR study deepens this crisis by showing the reaction **fundamentally produces branched rather than linear sugars** \u2014 meaning glucose cannot be a direct formose product under the conditions studied. Among 16 possible aldohexose stereoisomers plus 8 ketohexose isomers plus branched isomers, obtaining glucose specifically requires either remarkable selectivity or post-synthesis selection mechanisms.\n\nBenner's \"asphalt problem\" (*Accounts of Chemical Research*, 2012, 45:2025\u20132034) captures the broader challenge: prebiotic systems \"DEVOLVE to give uselessly complex mixtures\" unless reactants are \"presented in a specific order in large amounts.\" Possible solutions include mineral-guided selectivity (borate constraining products, molybdate converting branched to linear forms), environmental compartmentalization (different reaction steps in different microenvironments), and selective stabilization (thermodynamic and kinetic trapping of glucose in its exceptionally stable \u03b2-pyranose form).\n\n### Sugar stability constrains viable environments\n\nLarralde, Robertson, and Miller's 1995 study remains definitive: sugars decompose rapidly under prebiotic conditions, with ribose half-life of **73 minutes at 100\u00b0C** at pH 7. Alkaline conditions (needed for the formose reaction) accelerate decomposition further through enolization, retro-aldol cleavage, and saccharinic acid formation. Acidic conditions promote dehydration to 5-hydroxymethylfurfural and levulinic acid. This creates a fundamental tension: sugar synthesis requires conditions that simultaneously destroy the products.\n\nBorate stabilization partially resolves this, but borate also inhibits the formose reaction by sequestering reactive intermediates \u2014 suggesting that **sugar formation and stabilization must occur in separate locations** connected by transport. Wet-dry cycling in borate-rich pools offers one resolution: synthesis during the wet alkaline phase, stabilization during drying as borate esters strengthen, and selective release upon rehydration.\n\n### Chirality amplification has plausible mechanisms but remains undemonstrated for glucose\n\nBiology uses exclusively D-sugars. Cooper and Rios (*PNAS*, 2016) detected D-enantiomeric excesses of **33\u201355%** for sugar acids in carbonaceous meteorites, demonstrating that abiotic processes can produce chiral bias. Recent work on the Chiral-Induced Spin Selectivity (CISS) effect (Ozturk et al., *PNAS*, 2022, 119:e2204765119) proposes that spin-polarized electrons from magnetite deposits under solar UV could break chiral symmetry. Blackmond's group demonstrated that **1% excess of L-amino acids can produce 100% chiral purity** in sugar-amino acid cross-chirality transfer experiments. A 2025 *PNAS* framework proposes that homochirality propagates from a single nucleic acid precursor (ribose aminooxazoline) through genome \u2192 peptides \u2192 metabolites \u2014 but analysis of pristine Bennu and Ryugu samples challenges the hypothesis that solar system amino acid bias drove biological homochirality, suggesting it originated during terrestrial prebiotic chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: toward a multi-pathway, multi-environment synthesis network\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of glucose cannot be explained by any single pathway. The evidence points toward a **convergent, multi-source model** in which several mechanisms contribute glucose and its precursors:\n\nThe most promising near-term experimental directions are **Weber's iron hydroxide catalysis** (selective ketohexose formation at 25\u00b0C with subsequent isomerization to glucose), **Benner's mineral-guided borate-molybdate cycles** (with potential extension from pentoses to hexoses), **extraterrestrial delivery** of glycolaldehyde and pre-formed sugars (now confirmed by Bennu glucose detection), and **electrochemical CO\u2082-to-sugar pathways** that mimic prebiotic energy flows. The cyanosulfidic approach, while powerful for C2\u2013C5 intermediates, has not been extended to selective hexose production.\n\nFor an agentic AI synthesis network, the critical design implications are threefold. First, **formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde initiation** is the primary bottleneck (barrier 26.9\u201345.3 kcal/mol) and should be treated as a separate module requiring either photochemical, electrochemical, or delivery-based solutions. Second, **the C3 \u2192 C6 pathway** should branch through both direct C3 + C3 aldol condensation (yielding fructose, then glucose via isomerization) and stepwise C1 addition through C4 and C5 intermediates, with mineral catalysts (goethite, borate, molybdate) guiding selectivity at each stage. Third, **environmental cycling** \u2014 alternating between alkaline synthesis conditions and neutral/borate-stabilized storage \u2014 is essential to balance production against degradation. The field remains highly divided between terrestrial hot-spring advocates (Benner, Deamer), submarine vent proponents (Russell, Lane), and cyanosulfidic systems chemists (Sutherland), with Krishnamurthy's 2025 results forcing reconsideration of the most fundamental assumptions about formose chemistry's role in prebiotic sugar synthesis.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: The network is strong conceptually and clearly literature-aware, with good multi-environment integration and a sensible recognition that glucose likely emerged from convergent sources rather than a single clean pathway. Topology is adequate: it has sufficient node counts, clear hubs, and multiple convergence points. The best-supported modules are cyanosulfidic production of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde, goethite-catalyzed condensation of glyceraldehyde to ketohexoses, extraterrestrial delivery of glycolaldehyde/glucose, and borate-assisted phosphorylation/stabilization. The weakest modules are the hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde step and especially the canonical formose initiation from formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde, which the supplied literature identifies as the principal bottleneck and, under mild conditions, likely nonproductive for linear sugars. The network also overstates formose relevance to glucose because the 2025 literature suggests mild formose systems preferentially yield branched sugars. Another issue is schema-level incompleteness relative to the original network requirements: mineral agents and reaction conditions are not specified here, so environmental plausibility cannot be fully verified, and some reaction environments are too generic (notably biochemical-stage sugar isomerizations). Literature alignment is good overall because the network explicitly acknowledges the unsolved selectivity problem, uses Weber's goethite chemistry appropriately, includes Bennu delivery, and avoids claiming a single selective glucose synthesis. However, because several central reactions remain weakly grounded or under-specified, the network does not reach approval threshold.\n- Issues: ['This pathway is topologically coherent and captures the literature logic of vent-derived C1 feedstocks feeding surface sugar chemistry, then mild downstream isomerization to glucose. Its main weakness is the formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde initiation step, which the literature identifies as the central bottleneck and likely kinetically disfavored relative to Cannizzaro chemistry. Hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde is plausible only as a low-yield feedstock module, not a robust direct production route. The strongest element is the use of goethite-catalyzed C3+C3 condensation to fructose, which is well aligned with Weber-type mineral-guided ketohexose formation. The final fructose-to-glucose conversion is chemically reasonable, though assignment to a generic biochemical stage rather than a mineral-guided or alkaline equilibration environment is less well grounded.', 'This is one of the better pathways because it uses cyanosulfidic chemistry to bypass the worst formaldehyde dimerization bottleneck while still allowing hydrothermal C1 input and environmental convergence. The cyanosulfidic generation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde is strongly literature supported, and the goethite-mediated condensation to fructose is also well supported. The weaker point is that formaldehyde remains in the pathway via homologation, so some dependence on the problematic vent/formose module persists. Overall, this is a credible convergent route but still falls short of approval because the hydrothermal formaldehyde production step is underdefined and the later glucose isomerization context is not tightly specified.', 'This pathway is structurally similar to P3 but weaker because the sorbose-to-glucose conversion is less direct and less commonly emphasized than fructose-to-glucose equilibration in the literature. Sorbose is indeed a reported product of goethite-catalyzed glyceraldehyde condensation, so the branch is justified up to ketohexose formation. However, the final conversion to glucose is under-supported without a clearer mechanistic and environmental context. This route is plausible as a minor equilibration branch, not a primary glucose-producing pathway.', 'This route compounds two major weaknesses: the problematic formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde initiation and the relatively under-supported sorbose-to-glucose endpoint. While the environmental structure is reasonable, the chemistry is not competitive with the better-supported fructose branch. The literature suggests sorbose is a legitimate product of goethite-catalyzed C3 condensation, but not the best route onward to glucose.', 'The tetrose-assisted branch is chemically conceivable within broader formose chemistry, but literature support for this specific route to glucose is much weaker than for direct C3+C3 ketohexose formation. The network summary says this pathway reaches the glucose pool through the tetrose branch, yet the explicit listed reactions do not clearly connect tetroses onward to a unique C6 product other than by relying on generic formose complexity. Given the 2025 evidence favoring branched sugars in mild formose systems, this pathway is especially uncertain.', 'The initial cyanosulfidic module is strong, but the tetrose-assisted extension to C6 is less well supported than the simpler direct glyceraldehyde condensation route. This pathway appears to mix a strong literature-backed C2/C3 generation scheme with a weaker generalized formose branch. It is possible, but not a compelling best path to glucose.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.83\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and substantially better than a naive formose-only glucose network. It contains adequate molecule and reaction counts, multiple hubs, multiple convergence points, and clear environmental interconnection from hydrothermal feedstocks and surface photochemistry into later sugar assembly and stabilization. Its overall strategy aligns well with the literature conclusion that glucose should be treated as a convergent product of multiple modules rather than a single selective route. The strongest parts are the cyanosulfidic production of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde, the goethite-catalyzed C3+C3 condensation to ketohexoses, borate-assisted glucose stabilization/phosphorylation, and inclusion of extraterrestrial delivery. These are all well supported by the research findings.\n\nThe main weaknesses are chemical specificity and literature fidelity in several weaker branches. The hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde module is too optimistic as written. The formaldehyde-driven formose modules are correctly described as weak, but still somewhat overused given the 2025 evidence that mild formose conditions preferentially generate branched sugars rather than linear glucose precursors. Pentose-plus-formaldehyde extension to hexoses and the generic ketohexose-to-glucose step are underdefined and less experimentally anchored than the rest of the network. The glyoxylate branch also omits the major unresolved problem of DHF supply. Another issue is schema-level completeness relative to the requested network standard: the summarized network does not show reaction-specific mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface step, nor reaction-level literature citations in the reasoning fields, so full literature-alignment compliance is incomplete.\n\nOverall, this is a good but not approval-level network under the strict >=0.9 criterion. It is conceptually modern, convergent, and literature-aware, but several routes remain partly speculative and some required supporting detail is missing.\n- Issues: ['The upstream chemistry is good, but the sorbose-emphasizing branch is less coherent as a route to glucose. Sorbose is a documented product of goethite-catalyzed glyceraldehyde condensation, yet conversion from sorbose to glucose is far less direct and less supported than fructose-to-glucose isomerization. As described, the pathway appears to rely on the generic ketohexose-to-glucose step without identifying a plausible sorbose-specific rearrangement sequence.', 'This pathway is explicitly labeled low-yield and should indeed be treated cautiously. The hydrothermal CO2-to-formaldehyde step is weakly established in prebiotic vent models and not well supported as a direct productive source under the generic reaction statement given. The formaldehyde-to-glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde initiation step is the major kinetic bottleneck identified in the literature and, under mild conditions, recent work argues that formose chemistry preferentially generates branched rather than linear sugars. The later C3-to-ketohexose module is much stronger than the initial feedstock generation module.', 'This stepwise formaldehyde-extension pathway is substantially weaker than the direct C3+C3 condensation route. The initial hydrothermal formaldehyde generation is uncertain, and the pentose-plus-formaldehyde extension to a productive hexose pool is only loosely supported in the literature compared with the better-established glyceraldehyde-to-ketohexose route. Given the 2025 evidence that mild formose conditions favor branched products, this pathway likely overstates the viability of linear sugar extension.', 'The cyanosulfidic front end is strong and well supported, but extending it through pentoses to glucose is not strongly grounded in the cited literature. The research specifically notes that continued cyanosulfidic homologation reaches tetroses and pentoses without having been extended to selective hexose production. This pathway therefore bridges a literature gap with a speculative pentose-plus-formaldehyde module.', 'The network correctly recognizes the glyoxylate scenario as cleaner than classical formose chemistry, but this implementation inherits the major literature caveat that prebiotic DHF production is not well established. The DHF plus glyceraldehyde chemistry is better supported for clean pentose ketose formation than for onward glucose production. The last steps toward glucose again rely on relatively weak pentose extension and generic isomerization assumptions.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glucose\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"A literature-guided convergent network is used in which glucose is not treated as the product of one selective prebiotic route, but as the outcome of multiple partially supported modules operating across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical settings. Strongly supported modules include hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde/formate feedstocks at vent analogs, cyanosulfidic photochemical production of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, goethite-catalyzed C3+C3 condensation of glyceraldehyde to ketohexoses, borate/molybdate-guided stabilization and sugar interconversion in evaporitic surface environments, and direct extraterrestrial delivery of glycolaldehyde and glucose. In line with the supplied literature, canonical formose chemistry is included only as a low-confidence feeder module because mild formose systems preferentially generate branched sugars and formaldehyde dimerization is a major bottleneck. The network therefore emphasizes hub molecules formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, fructose, and glucose, with environmental cycling from hydrothermal feedstock generation to surface sugar assembly and finally biochemical stabilization/phosphorylation.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid/formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"sulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"HO3PS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"thiophosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"thiophosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      