"phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H12O7", "iupac_name": "2,3,4,5,6-pentahydroxyhexanoic acid", "common_name": "gluconic acid/gluconate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12O7/c7-1-2(8)3(9)4(10)5(11)6(12)13/h2-5,7-11H,1H2,(H,12,13)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde/formate feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent analog, pH 9-11; low-yield vent feedstock generation rather than selective sugar synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 across FeS-type catalytic surfaces generates reduced C1 products, including formaldehyde and formate, that can seed downstream surface chemistry.", "reasoning": "Included as a low-yield hydrothermal feeder module because the literature report explicitly cites Lane-group vent analog proof-of-principle CO2 reduction to formaldehyde under Lost City-like alkaline vent conditions and notes formaldehyde as a key C1 entry point, but also emphasizes that this is not a robust selective glucose route and should not be overstated (Pinto et al., 1980; Roldan et al., 2015; research summary citing Lane-group vent reactor work)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Thiophosphate generation in cyanosulfidic surface chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral-assisted UV photochemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated surface pool; thiophosphate formed from reduced phosphorus species oxidized in the presence of sulfide under UV"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven sulfur-phosphorus redox chemistry generates thiophosphate, an improved photoreductant for subsequent HCN homologation chemistry.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature identifies thiophosphate as a much more effective photoreductant than H2S alone in cyanosulfidic sugar precursor synthesis, though natural generation depends on reduced phosphorus availability and UV/sulfide chemistry. This connector step is necessary to represent the experimentally validated 2023 cyanosulfidic regime (Ritson & Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of HCN to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with thiophosphate-enabled reduction", "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate-buffered pH 6.5; UV-active surface environment; overall glycolaldehyde yield about 34%"}, "mechanism": "Reductive homologation of HCN under UV photoredox conditions forms C2 carbohydrate precursors directly, bypassing the formaldehyde dimerization bottleneck.", "reasoning": "This is one of the strongest literature-supported entry routes to sugar chemistry. The report highlights direct glycolaldehyde formation from HCN via UV-driven cyanosulfidic chemistry and specifically notes improved yields with thiophosphate at pH 6.5 (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of HCN-derived intermediates to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with thiophosphate-enabled reduction", "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate buffer around pH 6.5; evaporation/concentration step; overall glyceraldehyde yield about 14%"}, "mechanism": "Continued reductive homologation extends C2 glycolaldehyde chemistry to the C3 sugar glyceraldehyde under UV-driven cyanosulfidic conditions.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde formation by cyanosulfidic reductive homologation as a central alternative to classical formose initiation and one of the best-established prebiotic routes to sugar precursors (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Low-confidence formose initiation and propagation to glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "alkaline mineral-rich evaporitic pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "classical formose-like alkaline regime; highly nonselective; included only as a weak feeder because Cannizzaro side reaction dominates and mild systems produce branched sugars"}, "mechanism": "Autocatalytic aldol/isomerization network beginning from formaldehyde produces a heterogeneous pool of C2-C5 sugars once glycolaldehyde crosses a threshold concentration, but with extensive side reactions and degradation.", "reasoning": "This reaction is included only to reflect the canonical literature route while explicitly downgrading its confidence. The supplied report states that formaldehyde dimerization is the principal kinetic bottleneck, Cannizzaro disproportionation is favored, and a 2025 NMR study indicates mild formose chemistry fundamentally yields branched rather than linear sugars. Thus this module is a low-confidence contributor to precursor pools, not a primary glucose route (Butlerov, 1861; Breslow, 1959; Appayee & Breslow, 2014; Socha et al., 1980; Tran et al., 2023; Omran et al., 2020; Pulletikurti et al., 2025; Nishijima et al., 2026)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Glyceraldehyde-dihydroxyacetone isomerization", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "basic mineral-assisted isomerization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Lobry de Bruyn-Alberda van Ekenstein transformation; equilibrium favors ketotriose under basic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Aldose-ketose interconversion converts glyceraldehyde into dihydroxyacetone through carbonyl migration.", "reasoning": "The report identifies glyceraldehyde as the central branch point and notes its isomerization to dihydroxyacetone under basic conditions as a core feature of prebiotic sugar networks. Mineral support is included to satisfy surface-agent requirements and to reflect stabilization/organization in evaporitic mineral environments (Breslow, 1959; Appayee & Breslow, 2014; Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Stepwise sugar growth from glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde to tetrose and pentose pools", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "molybdate-bearing minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "338K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-molybdate-calcium guided sugar rearrangement network", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hands-off mineral-guided system around 65C; borate stabilizes sugars and molybdate promotes rearrangements toward linear species"}, "mechanism": "Aldol growth and rearrangement of lower sugars produce tetrose and pentose pools, while borate complexes suppress degradation and molybdate promotes rearrangement toward biologically relevant linear sugars.", "reasoning": "The research highlights borate as the most important sugar stabilizer and notes combined borate, molybdate, and calcium minerals guide tetrose, pentose, and heptose formation in hands-off experiments at 65C. This provides a literature-backed way to represent stepwise sugar growth without overclaiming direct selective glucose synthesis (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011; Furukawa et al., 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Glyoxylate dimerization to dihydroxyfumarate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-organized evaporitic pool chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "included as a speculative connection because the literature emphasizes that no known robust prebiotic source of DHF has yet been demonstrated"}, "mechanism": "Carboxylated C2 building blocks are linked into the formal glyoxylate dimer dihydroxyfumarate, enabling cleaner downstream ketose formation chemistry.", "reasoning": "The glyoxylate scenario is explicitly discussed in the supplied report as chemically cleaner than formose chemistry, but the report also stresses that prebiotic DHF supply is unresolved. This connector is therefore marked speculative yet necessary to represent the literature-recognized glyoxylate route (Eschenmoser, 2007; Sagi et al., 2012; Krishnamurthy group, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "DHF plus glyceraldehyde gives clean pentose ketose pool", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "molybdate-bearing minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-guided glyoxylose-like aldol chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "clean ketose-forming chemistry; literature reports about 60% yield to xylulose/ribulose from DHF + glyceraldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Dihydroxyfumarate reacts with glyceraldehyde to produce pentose ketoses through selective aldol chemistry distinct from the messy formose network.", "reasoning": "The report specifically notes experimental validation that DHF plus glyceraldehyde gives xylulose and ribulose in roughly 60% yield with clean ketose selectivity and no detectable aldoses. This branch is therefore included as a better-defined alternative to canonical formose chemistry, while acknowledging unresolved DHF sourcing (Sagi et al., 2012; Krishnamurthy group, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Goethite-catalyzed C3 plus C3 condensation to ketohexose pool", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["goethite (FeOOH)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "goethite (FeOOH)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5-6; mild aqueous conditions; no hexose decomposition observed even after 96 days; reported products include sorbose 15.2%, fructose 12.9%, psicose 6.1%, tagatose 5.6%"}, "mechanism": "Surface-catalyzed aldol condensation of glyceraldehyde molecules yields a stable ketohexose pool dominated by fructose and sorbose under mild conditions.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct literature-supported branch toward C6 sugars. The report identifies Weber's iron hydroxide/goethite chemistry as one of the most promising modules for prebiotic hexose synthesis, specifically under mild pH 5-6 and 25C conditions with substantial ketohexose yields and excellent stability (Weber, 1992; Jong et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Pentose/tetrose plus formaldehyde extension to ketohexose pool", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "molybdate-bearing minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-molybdate guided aldol extension", "aqueous": "true", "other": "included as a lower-confidence extension module reflecting literature recommendation to consider C4+C2 and C5+C1 routes to hexoses, not as a selective demonstrated glucose synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise aldol extension of stabilized tetrose/pentose pools by C1 addition expands carbon skeletons into a broader ketohexose pool.", "reasoning": "The research summary explicitly states that hexose formation can proceed through C4+C2 and C5+C1 routes in addition to C3+C3, and recommends such branching in network design. However, it also makes clear that selective glucose formation by these routes has not been demonstrated, so this reaction is retained as a speculative but literature-motivated connector rather than a strong core route (Breslow, 1959; Appayee & Breslow, 2014; Kim et al., 2011; research summary conclusion)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ketohexose pool equilibration to fructose", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "molybdate-bearing minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-338K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-guided ketohexose equilibration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild surface pool equilibration; borate traps/stabilizes cyclic sugars and molybdate can assist linearization/rearrangement chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Interconversion within the ketohexose pool enriches fructose as an accessible precursor to glucose through subsequent aldose-ketose rearrangement.", "reasoning": "The report stresses that prebiotic C3+C3 condensation primarily yields ketohexoses such as fructose and sorbose, with fructose being the most direct precursor to glucose by subsequent Lobry de Bruyn-type rearrangement. Borate and molybdate are included beca